ACT I. SCENE 1.

Simo tells his srcedman Sosia of the early life and disposition of his son Pamphilus; of thelove ofthe latterfor Glycerium, and its accidental discovery; of the consequent refusal ot' Chremes to allow his daughter Philumena to marry Pamphilus; finally, of his (Simo's) pretence that the match is nevertheless to take place, in order that he may test the obedience of his son.

Thus Terence, following his ordinary practice, uses the first scene to give us such information about the position of afsaIrs as enables us to understand the action of the play.
